Neural networks are a type of machine learning that is used to create models for computer vision tasks like object detection. They are inspired by the brain's visual cortex (where we process visual information) and use a similar layered architecture. The first layer is called the input layer, and it receives raw data from the outside world, such as an image. The next layer is the hidden layer, where information from the input layer is processed and combined to create new hidden features. The last layer is called the output layer and it produces a result, such as classifying an image as a dog, car, person, etc.

So PEFT balances these two approaches: still run batch fine-tuning, but use an L2 weight decay regularization mechanism on the network parameters after each batch that scales inversely to the size of your batch, in order to improve monotonic convergence and fine-tune on one shot. The parameters update so slowly in fine-tune-one-shot that running one batch at time is actually pretty fast.

The first, known as DenyHosts, can be used along with pledge to harden SSH further against brute-force password attacks. When DenyHosts is enabled, cryptographic hashes of the source IP addresses of all attempted login failures subsequent to a specified number of unsuccessful login attempts in quick succession are recorded in the file /etc/hosts.deny. The file is modeled after the well-known junior high school image sharing technique from the 1990s that was known as "chain letters", in that each cryptographic hash of an IP address is followed by a sequence of other addresses who have allegedly been suspected of varying degrees of SSHOF activity. "Backchaining" refers to the checking of packets by working backwards from the last known IP address supposed to be part of the chain. dhclient and pppd are configured by default to discard packets from IP addresses listed in /etc/hosts.deny and let the OSAs tender notice of failed login attempts.
